'''Uto Shrine''' (善知鳥神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Aomori, Aomori|ja|青森市|12=draft}}, Yasukata, Aomori Prefecture. Its former shrine rank was {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|12=draft}}.

== Deities ==

The shrine enshrines the {{ill|Munakata Sanjojin|ja|宗像三女神|1=Three Munakata Goddesses|12=draft}}, known as deities of the sea and maritime safety: {{ill|Ichikishimahime-no-Mikoto|ja|市杵島姫命|1=Ichikishimahime|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tagitsuhime-no-Mikoto|ja|多岐津姫命|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Tagirihime-no-Mikoto|ja|多紀理姫命|12=draft}}. Additional deities worshipped include {{ill|Ukanomitama|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto|ja|倉稲魂命|12=draft}}, {{ill|Miyabime-no-Mikoto|ja|宮比命|12=draft}}, {{ill|Sarutahiko Ōkami|lt=Sarutahiko-no-Mikoto|ja|猿田彦命|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Watatsumi|lt=Watatsumi-no-Mikoto|ja|海津見大神|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==

According to legend, during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Ingyo|ja|允恭天皇|12=draft}}, a courtier named {{ill|Uto Yasukata|ja|善知鳥安方|12=draft}} was exiled to Sotogahama. Inspired by a divine dream of Takakura Myojin, he built a small shrine on the tidal flats and enshrined the {{ill|Munakata Sanjojin|ja|宗像三女神|1=Three Munakata Goddesses|12=draft}}. Upon Yasukata's death, an unfamiliar bird appeared near the shrine. The male bird called "Uto," while the female bird called "Yasukata." Locals revered these birds as Yasukata’s incarnations. However, when a hunter mistakenly shot the male bird, the fields were ravaged, and the hunter died mysteriously, believed to be a curse. The male bird was then respectfully buried.

During the time of {{ill|Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|ja|坂上田村麻呂|12=draft}}, the shrine had fallen into ruin but was rebuilt under his command during the {{ill|Daido era|ja|大同|12=draft}}. The shrine was later patronized by the {{ill|Nanbu clan|ja|南部氏|12=draft}} during their rule and continued to receive support from the {{ill|Tsugaru clan|ja|津軽氏|12=draft}} after their rise in the Edo period. In the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代|12=draft}}, the shrine was designated a {{ill|Gosha|ja|郷社|12=draft}} in 1873 and elevated to a {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|12=draft}} in 1876. In 1907, as a part of the [[Shrine Consolidation Policy]] it incorporated the local {{ill|Inari Shrine|ja|稲荷神社|12=draft}} in July and {{ill|Watatsumi Shrine|ja|海津見神社|12=draft}} in September.

In December 2020, the shrine began offering {{ill|ema|ja|絵馬|12=draft}} in collaboration with the {{ill|Virtual YouTuber|ja|バーチャルYouTuber|12=draft}} {{ill|Aomori Rinko|ja|青森りんこ|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Collaboration Ema Now Available: Uto Shrine × "Aomori Rinko"|url=https://www.navitabi.jp/article/3831|website=Navitabi North Tohoku|accessdate=2021-01-14}}</ref>

== Related Articles ==

* {{ill|Rhinoceros auklet|ja|ウトウ|12=draft}} (Uto/sea bird)
* {{ill|Utou|ja|善知鳥|12=draft}} (Noh play)
* {{ill|Shikō Munakata|ja|棟方志功|12=draft}} – a printmaker and artist who spent his childhood near the shrine.

