'''Uto Shrine''' (善知鳥神社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in [[:en:Aomori|Aomori, Aomori]], Yasukata, Aomori Prefecture. Its former shrine Rank was {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|lt=Ken-sha|1=Modern_system_of_ranked_Shinto_shrines#Metropolitan_and_Prefectural_Shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prefectural Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度}}.

== Deities ==

The shrine enshrines the {{ill|Munakata Sanjojin|ja|宗像三女神|1=Three Munakata Goddesses|1=Three Munakata Goddesses|qq=Three Munakata Goddesses|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Munakata Sanjojin|13=User:Immanuelle/Three Munakata Goddesses|qq=}}, known as deities of the sea and maritime safety: {{ill|Ichikishima-hime-no-Mikoto|ja|市杵島姫命|1=Ichikishima-hime|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichikishima-hime-no-Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichikishima-hime|qq=||1=Ichikishima-hime|2=fr|3=Ichikishimahime|4=ja|5=イチキシマヒメ|6=zh|7=市寸島比賣命|8=ru|9=Итикишима-химэ|10=de|11=Ichikishima-hime}}, {{ill|Tagitsuhime-no-Mikoto|ja|多岐津姫命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tagitsuhime-no-Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to タギツヒメ}}, and {{ill|Tagirihime-no-Mikoto|ja|多紀理姫命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tagirihime-no-Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to タキリビメ}}. Additional deities worshipped include {{ill|Ukanomitama|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto|ja|倉稲魂命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ukanomitama|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to ウカノミタマ}}, {{ill|Miyabime-no-Mikoto|ja|宮比命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyabime-no-Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, {{ill|Sarutahiko Ōkami|lt=Sarutahiko-no-Mikoto|ja|猿田彦命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sarutahiko Ōkami|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to サルタヒコ}}, and {{ill|Watatsumi|lt=Watatsumi-no-Mikoto|ja|海津見大神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watatsumi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to ワタツミ}}.

== Overview ==

According to legend, during the reign of [[:en:Emperor Ingyō|Emperor Ingyo]], a courtier named {{ill|Uto Yasukata|ja|善知鳥安方|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Uto Yasukata|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} was exiled to Sotogahama. Inspired by a divine dream of Takakura Myojin, he built a small shrine on the tidal flats and enshrined the {{ill|Munakata Sanjojin|ja|宗像三女神|1=Three Munakata Goddesses|1=Three Munakata Goddesses|qq=Three Munakata Goddesses|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Munakata Sanjojin|13=User:Immanuelle/Three Munakata Goddesses|qq=}}. Upon Yasukata's death, an unfamiliar bird appeared near the shrine. The male bird called "Uto," while the female bird called "Yasukata." Locals revered these birds as Yasukata’s incarnations. However, when a hunter mistakenly shot the male bird, the fields were ravaged, and the hunter died mysteriously, believed to be a curse. The male bird was then respectfully buried.

During the time of [[:en:Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|Sakanoue no Tamuramaro]], the shrine had fallen into ruin but was rebuilt under his command during the [[:en:Datong (disambiguation)|Daido era]]. The shrine was later patronized by the [[:en:Nanbu clan|Nanbu clan]] during their rule and continued to receive support from the [[:en:Tsugaru clan|Tsugaru clan]] after their rise in the Edo period. In the [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji period]], the shrine was designated a {{ill|Gosha|ja|郷社|lt=Ken-sha|1=Modern_system_of_ranked_Shinto_shrines#District_shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gosha|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度}} in 1873 and elevated to a {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|lt=Ken-sha|1=Modern_system_of_ranked_Shinto_shrines#Metropolitan_and_Prefectural_Shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prefectural Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度}} in 1876. In 1907, as a part of the [[Shrine Consolidation Policy]] it incorporated the local [[:en:Inari shrine|Inari Shrine]] in July and {{ill|Watatsumi Shrine|ja|海津見神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watatsumi Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} in September.

In December 2020, the shrine began offering [[:en:Ema (Shinto)|Ema (Shinto)]] in collaboration with the [[:en:VTuber|Virtual YouTuber]] {{ill|Aomori Rinko|ja|青森りんこ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aomori Rinko|qq=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Collaboration Ema Now Available: Uto Shrine × "Aomori Rinko"|url=https://www.navitabi.jp/article/3831|website=Navitabi North Tohoku|accessdate=2021-01-14}}</ref>

